# Key Learning
Publicly shared images contain far more information than intended, restaurant names, venue signage, and event branding are all identifiable. Cross-platform correlation is powerful: a MotoGP photo, a food image, and a social media video from the same trip can be chained together to reconstruct a person's full itinerary. AI tools can assist in extracting non-obvious intelligence from images even without EXIF metadata present.

# What I Would Flag in a Real SOC
- Geolocation leakage via social media: posting event photos with visible venue signage or restaurant names inadvertently broadcasts location and schedule to threat actors
- The same OSINT chain used here (image > venue > social media > contact details) is exactly what a social engineer or adversary would use, staff awareness training is critical
- Phone number exposure through third-party tagged pages is difficult to audit or control, indirect exposure is often overlooked
- AI can infer time-of-day and context from image content even without EXIF data, scrubbing metadata alone is no longer sufficient
- Public Instagram videos from events can be used to name, identify, and potentially locate individuals in a real-world scenario
